14. Magn Reson Imaging Clin N Am. 2018 May;26(2):289-293. doi:10.1016/j.mric.2017.12.013. Epub 2018 Feb 21.How Does MR Imaging Help Care for the Breast Cancer Patient? Perspective of aMedical Oncologist.Raghavendra AS(1), Tripathy D(2).Author information: (1)Department of Breast Medical Oncology, Division of Cancer Medicine, TheUniversity of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center, 1515 Holcombe Boulevard, Houston, TX 77030, USA.(2)Department of Breast Medical Oncology, Division of Cancer Medicine, TheUniversity of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center, 1515 Holcombe Boulevard, Houston, TX 77030, USA. Electronic address: dtripathy@mdanderson.org.Although traditional assessment with clinical examination, mammogram, andultrasound is generally accepted for detection and staging of breast cancer, MRimaging is commonly used to detect occult cancers in the breast and regionalnodes in the early stage and to determine the extent of disease in patients with metastatic disease. Several studies have shown a variety of uses for MR imagingin the staging of breast cancer and assessment of treatment response in theneoadjuvant (preoperative) setting. This article reviews the impact of MR imagingin different settings on medical oncology decision-making in patients with breastcancer.Copyright Â© 2017 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.DOI: 10.1016/j.mric.2017.12.013 PMID: 29622134 